Spaghetti (Italian pronunciation: [spaˈɡetti], Vietnamese: spa-hate-ti), commonly known as spaghetti, is a long, small, cylindrical pasta. It is an essential part of traditional Italian cuisine. Like many other pastas, spaghetti is made from ground flour and water. Italian spaghetti is made from semolina flour made from durum wheat, but in many places it can be made from many other types of flour.

Originally, spaghetti was considerably long, but gradually shorter lengths of noodles became popular in the second half of the 20th century and at the present time spaghetti is mostly about 25-30 cm long. Many other pasta dishes are based on it.
